<ce:para>This work addresses the design and multi-objective optimization of complex reactive distillation columns through the use of feasible regions. Specifically, the use of feed qualities outside the traditional bounds (superheated and subcooled feeds), the reaction distribution and distributed feed are investigated. A cost indicator based on capacity variables is also introduced and the Pareto surface relating it with the reactive holdup is generated using the Îµ-constraint method, spanning over a varying number of total trays. The application of this technique is illustrated for an ideal system, which forms the base case, and two variants of it, which were obtained by modifying slightly the ratios of relative volatilities for reactants and products. The best tradeoff solutions for each system are identified, the operating conditions analyzed and a few heuristic rules inferred, which might be instrumental in guiding the selection of the most promising reactive distillation columns for a full design and costing.</ce:para>
